IN THE ARBITRAL TRIBUNAL
UNDER THE ARBITRATION AND CONCILIATION ACT, 1996

CASE: M/s Rajputana Infra Projects Pvt. Ltd. (Claimant)
VS
National Highways Authority of India, PIU Udaipur (Respondent)

SEAT: Rajasthan | PROJECT: NH-758, 45 KM Highway | CONTRACT VALUE: Rs. 112.65 Cr

1. CLAIM IN BRIEF
The Claimant was awarded the highway project under LOA dated 10.06.2024 for 24 months. The Claimant pleads that site possession was delayed by 78 days due to forest clearance and local obstructions, and that design approvals and material permissions were also delayed. It is further pleaded that despite substantial execution, certified dues were withheld, escalation was underpaid, and variation items were not fully valued.

The Claimant seeks a total award of Rs. 55.30 Cr under the following heads:
(a) Delay in site possession and consequent overhead loss: Rs. 14.85 Cr
(b) Price escalation (contractual formula): Rs. 9.75 Cr
(c) Variation/extra items: Rs. 11.40 Cr
(d) Idle machinery and labour: Rs. 6.25 Cr
(e) Loss of profit/opportunity: Rs. 8.90 Cr
(f) Other contractual dues and adjustments: balance component
Interest is sought at 12% p.a. from invocation till realization, with costs.

2. RESPONDENT'S DEFENCE / COUNTER POSITION
The Respondent disputes liability, pleads slow progress by Claimant, and justifies deductions and adverse contractual steps. The Respondent challenges the quantum methodology, especially on loss of profit and certain idle claims, and argues that not all delays are employer-attributable. It is also contended that notices were deficient and that Claimant did not mitigate costs.

3. ISSUES FRAMED
I. Whether delay in completion was primarily attributable to Respondent, and if yes, to what extent.
II. Whether Claimant is entitled to escalation and variation payments as claimed.
III. Whether idle charges are proved by contemporaneous records.
IV. Whether loss of profit is legally and factually established.
V. Relief, interest, and costs.

4. FINDINGS (SUMMARY DECISION)
Issue I: Decided substantially in favour of Claimant. Records show initial access and clearance delay materially affected progress. Employer-attributable delay established for a significant period.

Issue II: Decided partly in favour of Claimant. Escalation is contractually payable on accepted formula basis; variation entitlement proved for documented instructed works.

Issue III: Decided partly in favour of Claimant. Idle charges are allowed where logbooks, deployment sheets, and correspondence corroborate actual idling. Inflated/unlinked components disallowed.

Issue IV: Decided partly against Claimant. Loss of profit is not fully proved to the claimed extent. A reduced amount, if any, is allowed on conservative evidentiary basis.

5. OPERATIVE AWARD
Accordingly, the Tribunal awards:
(a) Net principal sum: Rs. 41.65 Cr payable by Respondent to Claimant.
(b) Interest: 8.5% p.a. from date of invocation until payment.
(c) Counter recoveries/LD: only limited adjustment of Rs. 2.15 Cr is sustained; remaining broad deductions rejected.
(d) Costs: major arbitration costs to be borne by Respondent.

6. DECREE / ENFORCEMENT / STAY NOTE
This award shall be enforceable in accordance with Section 36 of the A&C Act as a decree, subject to statutory challenge rights.
If Respondent files Section 34, no automatic stay shall operate; any stay must be by reasoned judicial order, ordinarily upon deposit/security conditions.
During High Court pendency, Claimant is at liberty to seek expedited hearing, compliance monitoring of stay conditions, and release of secured/undisputed components as permissible in law.

7. FINAL DIRECTION
Respondent shall comply with payment obligations under this award within the period fixed by law, failing which Claimant may initiate execution proceedings before the competent court.

